      Example:
        String bigString = "height is 10 meters, but height is not too big.";
        RegModel regModel = new RegModel(bigString);
        regModel.seek(0,2,(r)->{
         regModel.any().has("height").wspace().word();
        });
        System.out.println( regModel.ok() );
        
        int max = 2, min = 0; int count = 0;
        while( count<max && regModel.any().has("height").wspace().word().ok() ) {
         count++;
        }
        if(count<min) regModel.err();
        if(regModel.err() && count==0 && min==0) regModel.setOK();
        
        System.out.println( regModel.ok() );
        }
      Note:
      This method can be modified with modifiers such as can$(), not$(), etc.

      • any

        public RegModel any()
        It is select all rest characters to the begin of string if direction is right to the left.
        It is select all rest characters to the end of string if direction is left to the right.
        Example:
           String bigString = "Women, from Montreal.";
           RegModel regModel = new RegModel(bigString);
           regModel.has("from"); // => ok, marked CharSequence is 'from'
           regModel.any(); //=> ok, marked CharSequence is rest to the end ' Montreal.'
           regModel.toLeft$(); //=> change direction to search models from right to the left
           regModel.letter(); // => ok, marked CharSequence is 'from'
           regModel.any(); //=> ok, marked CharSequence is rest to the begin 'Women, '
        Returns:
        RegModel with marked the next CharSequence to the end.

      • fromStart$

        public RegModel fromStart$()
        Move the cursor to the start of string, next model selector have to start from begin of string.
        Example:
        private void fromStart$() {
          String bigString = "Women, from Montreal.";
          RegModel regModel = new RegModel(bigString);
          regModel.any(); //=> ok, by default search inside 'bigString', not from first character
          regModel.has("from"); // => ok, selected model is 'from'
          
          //Move the cursor to the start of string, next model selector have to start from begin of string.
          regModel.fromStart$();
          regModel.has("from"); // => err, 'from' is not from begin of 'bigString'
          
          regModel.setOK(); // change state to 'ok'. When state became is 'err', nothing isn't matching
          regModel.has("Women"); // => ok, selected model is 'Women'
        }
        Returns:
        Matches the beginning of the input.

      • not$

        public RegModel not$()
        A modifier that denies the next model.
        Example:
           String bigString = "Height 10 meters";
           RegModel regModel = new RegModel(bigString);
           regModel.fromStart$();
           regModel.not$().digits(); //=> ok, selected model is 'Height '
           regModel.digits(); //=> ok, selected model is '10'
        }
        Returns:
        Modifies the searched to match model to its mismatch.

      • if$

        public RegModel if$()
        RegModel modifier that allows further manipulation and search of the CharSequence in the RegModel, based on the output of the model used after it (whether there is a match or a mismatch).
        Example:
        String bigString = "This is CharSequence.Let's use if modifier for 4 it.";
        regModel regModel = new RegModel(bigString);
        regModel.if$() - start of if modifier
        .has("modifier") => ok, (34-42) 'modifier'
        .wspace() => ok, (42-43) ' '
        .has("for") => ok, (43-46) 'for'
        then$() - if true then do:
        .any().number(); => ok, (47-48) '4'
        if(regModel.ok()) {
        String ifTrueValue = regModel.get(); => "4"
        System.out.println("Selected model in then: "+ifTrueValue);
        }
        regModel.else$() - if false then do:
        .fromStart$() - search again from start of the CharSequence.
        .has("if")
        .any();
        if(regModel.ok()) {
        String ifFalseValue = regModel.get();
        System.out.println("Selected model in else: "+ifFalseValue);
        }
        regModel.endIf$(); - end of if modifier
        Note:
        Use modifier then$ in case of a match to access further manipulation and search of the CharSequence in the RegModel.
        Use modifier else$ in case of a mismatch to access further manipulation and search of the CharSequence in the RegModel.

      • then$

        public RegModel then$()
        Modifier used in case of a match (model after if$ modifier returns true boolean) to give access for further manipulation with the next model.

      • else$

        public RegModel else$()
        Modifier used in case of a mismatch (model after if$ modifier returns false boolean) to give access for further manipulation with the next model.

      • can$

        public RegModel can$()
        It is ok, if next model selector does not match anything.
        Example:
        private void can$() {
           String bigString = "Height 10 meters";
           RegModel regModel = new RegModel(bigString);
           regModel.fromStart$();
           regModel.can$().digits(); //=> ok, nothing is selected because the next characters are not digits, but it is ok.
           regModel.can$().not$().digits(); //=> ok, selected model is 'Height '
        }
        Returns:
        RegModel

      • since

        public RegModel since()

        Marks the next char after the current marked CharSequence as a starting point. Does not include the marked CharSequence!
        Requires usage of another model after it in order to mark the ending point of the since() model.

        Example:
        String bigString = "This is CharSequence.Let's use since model for it.";
        RegModel regModel = new RegModel(bigString);

        regModel.has("This") => ok, (0-4) "This"
        .since() -> (0-4) "This" , but it's not included in the since output.
        .any() -> (4-50) => ok, " is CharSequence.Let's use since model for it."
        .has("CharSequence"); => ok, (8-20) 'CharSequence'
        String sub = regModel.sinceSubstring(); => ok, (5-9) " is "
        Returns:
        Use sinceSubString() to get marked from since() model CharSequence.
        Use sinceRange() to get information about the starting index and the ending index of the from since() model CharSequence in the RegModel object.
